body:
Hi,

Could you try our latest binary: [https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build/results?buildId=90458&view=artifacts](https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build/results?buildId=90458&view=artifacts) ?

That has changed the error, now I get the following after updating my code to the new API:
```2019-10-20 13:09:44.923102435 [I:onnxruntime:onnx.log, kernel_registry.cc:271 TryFindKernel] Slice kernel is not supported in CUDAExecutionProvider Encountered following errors: 
2019-10-20 13:09:44.923126450 [I:onnxruntime:onnx.log, kernel_registry.cc:271 TryFindKernel] Squeeze kernel is not supported in CUDAExecutionProvider Encountered following errors: 
2019-10-20 13:09:44.923141124 [I:onnxruntime:onnx.log, kernel_registry.cc:271 TryFindKernel] Gemm kernel is not supported in CUDAExecutionProvider Encountered following errors: 
2019-10-20 13:09:44.923151946 [I:onnxruntime:onnx.log, kernel_registry.cc:271 TryFindKernel] Gemm kernel is not supported in CUDAExecutionProvider Encountered following errors:```
BTW, should I be using the C++ API instead of the C API since the C API seems to be undergoing a lot of changes.

The C API is finalized. It should have big changes in the future. 

These three lines are "Information", not the error. Could you please provide more logs?  Some thing like "[**E**:onnxruntime:"

Hi @snnn, thanks for pointing me to an updated build, here's the full output. There's no error lines, but in this case I count kernels not being supported by the CUDA provider for a basic neural network as an error. The network has two dense layers, nothing fancy.

Also, your answer on the API status doesn't make sense, is it finalised, or is it not finalised and hence "should have big changes in the future"? Perhaps I'm just misunderstanding your statement.

The C API is finalized. It should *NOT* have big changes in the future. Even if there are changes we'll maintain ABI compatibility. 

Can you share the model file? Based on this [file](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/cuda_execution_provider.cc), we have implemented cuda ops for the errors (Slice, Squeeze, Gemm) you've encountered in the logs. So we'll have to look at the model file to check if we've implemented these ops for the data types used in the model.

Try this one generated using tf2onnx:
https://bitbucket.org/williamjshipman/tensorflow-save-and-serve-blog-post/src/master/data/save_model_v1.onnx

There's also this one generated by keras2onnx:
https://bitbucket.org/williamjshipman/tensorflow-save-and-serve-blog-post/src/master/data/save_model_v2.onnx
